answers.body_markdown:
Problem was solved by adding an exclusion for the problematic dependency:

    &lt;dependency&gt;
	      &lt;groupId&gt;au.com.dius&lt;/groupId&gt;
	      &lt;artifactId&gt;pact-jvm-provider-spring_2.12&lt;/artifactId&gt;
	      &lt;version&gt;3.5.24&lt;/version&gt;
	      &lt;scope&gt;test&lt;/scope&gt;
			&lt;exclusions&gt;
		      &lt;exclusion&gt;
					&lt;groupId&gt;com.google.guava&lt;/groupId&gt;
					&lt;artifactId&gt;guava&lt;/artifactId&gt;
				      &lt;version&gt;31.1.0.redhat-00001&lt;/version&gt;
				&lt;/exclusion&gt;
			&lt;/exclusions&gt;
   		&lt;/dependency&gt;

My nexus guy says that the JBoss setup in the problematic eclipse version requires this Guava dependency and loads it before pact-jvm-provide-spring does. This guava version has problems, its jar is missing. But somehow it is selected by Maven. The other Eclipse instance does not have JBoss and another version of Guava is selected by Maven.

Maybe we have hit a Maven bug here: A dependency without jar file is being selected. Here is the POM which causes Maven to select this version of Guava:

    &lt;dependency&gt;
      &lt;groupId&gt;com.google.guava&lt;/groupId&gt;
      &lt;artifactId&gt;guava&lt;/artifactId&gt;
      &lt;version&gt;[10.+,)&lt;/version&gt;
      &lt;scope&gt;compile&lt;/scope&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;

So it is asking for a 10.+ version of Guava and Maven picks the one without a jar file.

